<br>
Over the past few years, a number of highly flattering biographies of Edward Teller have appeared, most recently the 1990 hagiography by Stanley Blumberg and Louis Panos. Fortunately, a new book from Pulitzer Prize-winning New York Times reporter William J. Broad begins to redress the imbalance by painting a portrait of Teller's darker side, showing a cunning and manipulative individual beneath the well-known veneer of buoyant optimism and bonhomie.<br>
<br>
Broad shows that when J. Robert Oppenheimer was stripped of his &quot;Q&quot; security clearance by the Atomic Energy Commission (AEC) in the summer of 1954 (a heresy trial Teller helped to engineer and direct), a voice of reason and restraint was banished forever from the councils of government, and the course of American nuclear weapons development was irrevocably changed.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, the absence of a strong countervailing personality created a vacuum into which stepped a master salesman against whom few dared to speak. Enter Teller, a latter-day Merlin who would, for the next 30 years-through no fewer than seven presidential administrations-dazzle and bewilder the nation's leaders, most of whom had little scientific education, with claims of technological prowess that were often simply unachievable.<br>
<br>
Teller's quest for the impossible had its roots in the first concept of the hydrogen bomb, an idea that former AEC Chairman Gordon Dean, in the November 1954 Bulletin, called &quot;a bomb, which as then conceived, should never have been built-and never was built.&quot;<br>
<br>
After a workable hydrogen bomb was designed, with considerable inspiration from Stanislaw Ulam, attention turned to a so-called &quot;clean&quot; bomb-a thermonuclear weapon that would produce little or no fallout resulting from fission processes. Edward Teller and his new weapons laboratory at Livermore, California, were in the forefront of &quot;clean&quot; weapons research.<br>
<br>
Although the project eventually produced &quot;clean&quot; strategic weapons, primarily large, heavy, high-yield aerial bombs and missile warheads unsuitable for tactical battlefield use, the search for small, &quot;clean&quot; weapons was generally unsuccessful. Still, throughout the late 1950s, Teller and his Livermore colleagues repeatedly told Congress and President Dwight D. Eisenhower that successful, small tactical &quot;clean&quot; warheads were just around the corner, and that atmospheric nuclear tests should continue to help design them. But the corner never got any closer; in June 1958, AEC spokesman Morse Salisbury noted that &quot;we have made essentially no progress in our attempts to reduce substantially the size of feasible clean weapons&quot; (see &quot;Teller and the 'Clean' Bomb Episode,&quot; May 1988 Bulletin).<br>
<br>
In 1983, Teller gained the ear of then-President Ronald Reagan, a Hollywood actor and GE spokesman turned politician, who was bereft of scientific education. Speaking of desk-sized weapons that would protect the entire countryside from the &quot;Evil Empire's&quot; missiles, Teller proposed a &quot;peace shield&quot; that could be available within a few years, which would guarantee that no nuclear missile warhead would ever explode over the United States.<br>
<br>
Teller's claims for this program, aptly dubbed &quot;Star Wars&quot; after another contemporary science fiction epic, proved to be no more feasible than either his first hydrogen bomb design or the fabled &quot;clean&quot; tactical bomb. Star Wars became a $25 billion pork-barrel Disneyland for high-energy physicists, with both U.S. nuclear weapons laboratories embarking on extremely expensive research and hardware development projects for the navy, army, and air force.<br>
<br>
A favorite Teller proposal during this period was the &quot;nuclear bomb-pumped X-ray laser,&quot; a space-borne defensive battle station that would destroy incoming nuclear warheads high in space, which was to be ready for deployment in as little as four years. Several nuclear tests were conducted in Nevada to perfect the device; according to Teller, these experiments resulted in laser wavelengths &quot;1,000 times shorter than lasers of visible light.&quot; Nonetheless, after 12 years of inconclusive research and the expenditure of billions of dollars, work on the X-ray laser was stopped, and a poorly conceived, shamelessly oversold high-technology project came to a fitting end as a scientific curiosity with little practical military value.<br>
<br>
In 1954, speaking of Teller's misguided early attempts at a hydrogen bomb, Hans Bethe wrote that Teller &quot;was blamed at Los Alamos for leading the laboratory, and indeed the whole country, into an adventurous program on the basis of calculations which he himself must have known to be very incomplete.&quot; The same can be said of Teller's promotion of the X-ray laser more than 30 years later.<br>
<br>
Broad's new book is a thoroughly annotated and highly detailed sequel to his 1985 Star Warriors, the story of Teller protégé Lowell Wood and the scientists at Livermore who pursued Teller's dreams of an invulnerable peace shield. In Teller's War, Broad details Teller's persistent salesmanship of Star Wars and his ceaseless attacks on his critics. (Oppenheimer was not Teller's only victim sentenced to a scientific Elba-rising Livermore physicist-manager Roy Woodruff was forced to resign after Teller and Wood essentially wrested control of the program away from him; Roger Batzel, then Livermore's director, refused to interfere with Teller's sales efforts, which bypassed normal laboratory channels.)<br>
<br>
Broad explains how Teller, with the collusion of strategically placed and selected allies, and under the guise of national security, repeatedly sold to gullible politicians costly and extravagant nuclear weapons programs that were shielded by classification from external analysis or proper peer review.<br>
<br>
Teller and Wood's sales efforts continue today, this time on behalf of the Brilliant Eyes and Brilliant Pebbles space defense concepts. In the summer of 1991, Congress directed the Strategic Defense Initiative Organization to develop a limited anti-missile defense system that complied with the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile (ABM) Treaty, to be deployed at the long-abandoned Grand Forks, North Dakota, ABM field. President George Bush plans to spend $5.4 billion on Star Wars research in 1992, a 31 percent increase over the project's 1991 budget; $727 million of this is for Brilliant Pebbles and Brilliant Eyes.<br>
<br>
Teller, speaking through the public relations office at Livermore, has stated that the events recounted by Broad are in the past and should not be dwelt upon any longer. But while ballistic missiles proliferate, and as long as there is a question of what type of anti-missile defense, if any, the United States can afford to deploy, Teller's influence in the high councils of state should be monitored closely, and, when necessary, contested vigorously by opponents who are not bound by the restraints of security clearances. Broad's new book performs an important public service in this respect by spotlighting a major scientific scandal of the 1980s.<br>
